# 🚀 feature request

### Relevant Package
This feature request is for @angular/router


### Description
I might be missing something that could make this possible. For example a custom builder would make this work. However, I believe this would be beneficial to the core angular application.

It's now common for some modules to use forRoot and forFeature that would return ModuleWithProviders. I believe it would be beneficial for the lazy loading of routes to support modules that would return ModuleWithProviders.

This allows them to configure pages data while still supporting lazy loading.





### Describe the solution you'd like
```

implementation: 
{
    path: 'catalog',
    loadChildren: () => import('@pacakge/catalog/core')
      .then(m => m.CatalogCoreModule.forRoot<ItemType>(
        {
          path: '',
          Groups: [
            {
              group: 'APC Equipment',
              categories: [
                {
                  category: 'item1',
                  type: ItemType.item1,
                  filter: {
                  }
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        })
      )
  },
```


modules: 

```
export class CatalogCoreModule {
  // Note: We are injecting the Router so it gets created eagerly...
  // constructor(@Optional() router: Router) { }

  /**
   * Creates and configures a module with all the router providers and directives.
   * Optionally sets up an application listener to perform an initial navigation.
   *
   * @param routes An array of `Route` objects that define the navigation paths for the application.
   * @return The new router module.
  */
  static forRoot<ItemType>(catalog: Catalog<ItemType>): ModuleWithProviders<CatalogCoreModule>;
  static forRoot(catalog: Catalog<any>): ModuleWithProviders<CatalogCoreModule> {

    return {
      ngModule: CatalogCoreModule,
      providers: [
        provideRoutes(this.catalogCategoriesToRoutes(catalog)),
      ],
    };
  }

  /**
   * Creates a module with all the router directives and a provider registering routes.
   */
  static forChild(): ModuleWithProviders<CatalogCoreModule> {
    return { ngModule: CatalogCoreModule, providers: [] };
  }

  private static filterToRoutes(path: string, filterOption?: CatalogFilterOption): Route {

    if (filterOption) {
      let route: Route = {
        path: path,
      }

      if (filterOption.component) {
        route = {
          ...route,
          ...{
            outlet: 'options',
            component: filterOption.component.component,
            loadChildren: filterOption.component?.loadChildren || undefined,
            children: filterOption.component?.children || undefined,
          }
        }
      } else {
        route = {
          ...route,
          component: SeOptionsComponent,
          resolve: {
            filter: filterOption.filters
          }
        }
      }

      return route;
    }
    return;
  }

  private static catalogCategoriesToRoutes(catalog: Catalog<any>): Routes {
    if (!catalog) {
      throw new NoCatalogConfig()
    }
    const childrenRoutes: Routes = [
      ...catalog.Groups
        .flatMap(group => group.categories)
        .flatMap((category) => {
          const routes: Routes = [];
          const filter = this.filterToRoutes(category.category, category.filter);
          if (filter) {
            debugger;
            routes.push(filter);
          }
          return routes;
        })
    ];
    return [
      {
        path: catalog?.path || '',
        component: SeCatalogContainer,
        children: [
          {
            path: '',
            outlet: 'search',
            component: catalog.search?.searchComponent?.component || SeSearchComponent,
            loadChildren: catalog.search?.searchComponent?.loadChildren || undefined,
            children: catalog.search?.searchComponent?.children || undefined,
          },
          ...childrenRoutes
        ]
      }
    ];
  }
}
```


### Describe alternatives you've considered
Alternative would be to create a new builder that would allow injection in. Another solution would be to allow the app level to use providers with muti and the module on create would then inject the configuration and provide the logic required. Issue with this solution it would provide much more overhead and development



You can also wrap the code around something similar to this

```
export const configure = (config: any) => {

  @NgModule({
    imports: [
      CatalogCoreModule.forRoot<ItemType>(config)
    ],
  })
  class CatalogViewModule { }
  return CatalogViewModule;
}

However thats not idea. 
```

#### Reproduction

See this repository as the StackBlitz template is not configured for v9 RC: https://github.com/benelliott/repro-cdk-overlay
 
 
#### Expected Behavior

What behavior were you expecting to see?

`CdkConnectedOverlay.backdropClick` events should be emitted within the Angular zone so that they are picked up by `ChangeDetectionStrategy.OnPush`.

#### Actual Behavior

Setting a value in a component based on the `backdropClick` event causes no changes under `OnPush` without a manual call to `ChangeDetectorRef.detectChanges`.

I think this is because in https://github.com/angular/components/blob/master/src/cdk/overlay/overlay-directives.ts#L380 the `backdropClick.emit` call needs to be run inside `NgZone.run`.

```
    if (this.hasBackdrop) {
      this._backdropSubscription = this._overlayRef.backdropClick().subscribe(event => {
        this.backdropClick.emit(event);
      });
    } else {
      this._backdropSubscription.unsubscribe();
    }
```

For some reason, this didn't cause issues under Angular/CDK v8 but it causes issues in Ivy, presumably due to internal changes in Ivy's change detector.

#### Environment

- Angular: 9.0.0-rc.14
- CDK/Material: 9.0.0-rc.9
- Browser(s): Chrome 79
- Operating System (e.g. Windows, macOS, Ubuntu): Windows 10
